<SessionPage
  title="Session 4 · C# constructors, properties, and state"
  heading="Give each object state, then choose its receiver"
  lede="Today’s win: construct two independent objects, keep their public state controlled, and distinguish a state-changing instance method from a type-level helper."
  backHref="/topics/csharp/"
  backLabel="C# sessions"
>
  <SessionSection title="A class is a shape; each object has its own state">
    <Callout>
      Constructor-set <code>get;</code> properties are fixed for each object after construction. A property with <code>private set;</code> can still change, but only through behavior inside the class.
    </Callout>
    <p>
      <code>RetryTracker</code> could represent retry state for a backend operation. Its operation name and limit are chosen when it is created. Its attempt count starts at zero and changes only when the tracker records an attempt.
    </p>
    <p>
      This is not a static-versus-instance vocabulary drill. The question is practical: which operation needs one selected tracker and its current state?
    </p>
  </SessionSection>

  <SessionSection title="One small stateful class">
    <Code code={classExample} lang="csharp" />
    <ul>
      <li><code>Operation</code> and <code>MaxAttempts</code> are assigned by the constructor and then read-only through the public API.</li>
      <li><code>Attempts</code> is readable by callers, but only this class can update it.</li>
      <li><code>RecordAttempt()</code> needs a particular tracker’s <code>Attempts</code> and <code>MaxAttempts</code>, so it is an instance method.</li>
      <li><code>IsValidMaxAttempts(...)</code> needs only its argument, so it is a static type-level helper.</li>
    </ul>
  </SessionSection>

  <SessionSection title="Read state and receiver together">
    <p>
      Calling <code>email.RecordAttempt()</code> selects the <code>email</code> object. It may change <code>email.Attempts</code>, but it cannot silently change <code>webhook.Attempts</code>: those are separate objects created from the same class.
    </p>
    <p>
      A static method has no implicit <code>this</code> object. Call it through <code>RetryTracker</code> and supply every value it needs explicitly.
    </p>
  </SessionSection>

  <SessionSection title="Two useful compiler failures" variant="warning">
    <p><code>RetryTracker.RecordAttempt()</code> fails because no tracker was selected, so there is no <code>Attempts</code> state to read or update.</p>
    <p><code>email.IsValidMaxAttempts(2)</code> fails because this helper belongs to the type. Use <code>RetryTracker.IsValidMaxAttempts(2)</code>.</p>
  </SessionSection>

  <ReplyTask id="learn:csharp/004:q1" copyText={replyText} difficulty={3}>
